Session data: <FileSystemSession {'csrf_token': '73d6365b8aa633ef80f25a424498bf7e7521ff7b', '_fresh': True, 'pdf_filename': '1c2adb7d00cbec5ce40f6dabc112791296b475c0e58206cf89a53d8948d0f435Core_Idea.pdf', 'number_of_chunks': 'Retrieved from Database', 'openAI_summary_PDF': '- Chapter sets scene for exploring entrepreneurial choices\n- Identifying a core idea is important for making choices in a venture\n- Core idea is fundamental opportunity and insight that venture is built on\n- Examples of ventures evolving from their core idea (Flickr, Slack)\n- Trap of describing venture by analogy to existing successful concept\n- Importance of stating core idea independent of key choices\n- Famous examples of core ideas for ventures such as Amazon, Google, Uber, etc.', 'openAI_summary_JSON_PDF': {'id': 'chatcmpl-73MDuen0PJthJFQFpElrHW1Ogn8V7', 'object': 'chat.completion', 'created': 1681034766, 'model': 'gpt-3.5-turbo-0301', 'usage': {'prompt_tokens': 2308, 'completion_tokens': 94, 'total_tokens': 2402}, 'choices': [{'message': {'role': 'assistant', 'content': '- Chapter sets scene for exploring entrepreneurial choices\n- Identifying a core idea is important for making choices in a venture\n- Core idea is fundamental opportunity and insight that venture is built on\n- Examples of ventures evolving from their core idea (Flickr, Slack)\n- Trap of describing venture by analogy to existing successful concept\n- Importance of stating core idea independent of key choices\n- Famous examples of core ideas for ventures such as Amazon, Google, Uber, etc.'}, 'finish_reason': 'stop', 'index': 0}]}, 'text2summarize_PDF': 'approach  and  way  of  thinking  that  will  help  them  get  started  in  a  new  field  or \n\ndomain.  \n\nThis  chapter  sets  the  scene  for  the  choices  that  will  be  explored  in  detail \n\nthroughout  the  rest  of  this  book.  Then,  it  will  help  you  understand  why  the \n\nchallenge  of  entrepreneurial  choice  is  difficult  and  unique,  and  also  give  you  a \n\nworking framework that you can use to make them.  \n\nForming a core idea: identifying what you can choose \n\nIn Chapter 3, we already saw that entrepreneurs have certain characteristics \n\nthat are part of their identity and skill set. They have a passion for particular values \n\nand  they  have  skills  that  may  give  them  an  unfair  advantage.  But  every \n\nentrepreneur  must  have  a  core  idea.  A  venture’s  core  idea  is  the  fundamental \n\nentrepreneurial opportunity and insight that the venture will be built on. The \n\ncore idea is something that is hard to come by and even harder to move away from. \n\nIndeed, in many respects, if you change your core idea, you are really founding an \n\nentirely new venture (See Box: If you change your idea, you have a new venture).  \n\nAlong with the entrepreneur themself, it is the thing that will not change as the \n\nventure evolves, and importantly, it gives the entrepreneur insight into the choices \n\nthey will have to make as they form their venture. In fact, the best way to identify \n\nthose choices is to know and be able to state very clearly what the core idea of \n\nthe venture is.  \n\nIf you change your idea, you have a new venture \n\nWhile entrepreneurs cannot really change their passion or their unfair advantage, ideas can \n\ncome and go. For each core idea, there are many possible strategies and entrepreneurial choice is about \n\nselecting between them. But some ventures form and their core idea changes. Here is a case in point. \n\nBefore  Instagram,  the  big startup  for  photo  sharing  was Flickr.  When  they  started  in  2002, \n\nFlickr’s  founders  had  another  idea.  For  Caterina  Fake  and  Stewart  Butterfield,  their  desire  was  to \n\ncreate a social game that drove interactions between people. A year later, their project called “Game \n\nNeverending” looked like it would never start. They were running out of money and the game was \n\nnot even developed yet. What they had, however, was a user-interface that allowed people to drag \n\ngame objects around. They then had the inspiration that user-interface could be a great way of sharing \n\n \n\x0cphotos instead. They could deploy Flickr quickly and thanks to a loan from the Canadian government, \n\nthey had enough runway left. \n\nFlickr involved a fundamentally different idea than Game Neverending. Fake and Butterfield \n\nwere very lucky that some of the development they had from doing one became inspiration for the \n\nother. So, while legally this all looked like the same company, conceptually it was a new and distinct \n\nventure. That new venture would prove to be lucrative with with Flickr selling to Yahoo in 2005 for \n\n$25 million. \n\nButterfield went on to try his hand at a gaming startup again in 2009 with a Vancouver based-\n\nstartup, Glitch. It failed but the founders noticed that an internal tool they had developed to allow \n\nbetter communication was a potentially powerful replacement for email. They chose to develop that \n\ninstead and launched the tool as Slack in 2015. In 2019, Slack went public with a value in excess of $15 \n\nbillion and, in 2020, sold to Salesforce for $27 billion. Once again, one idea had evolved, almost by \n\naccident, into another. \n\nThe examples of both Flickr and Slack show what happens when a venture starts in one place \n\nand  then  morphs  into  something  different.  What  is  striking  and  perhaps  unusual  is  how  far  the \n\nventure’s idea moved from its original. In reality, for most ventures, their core idea is something that \n\nis  fixed  and  does  not  change  even  as  the  venture  itself  might  evolve  to  look  like  something  very \n\ndifferent. Regardless, when framing all of the options available for a venture, it is useful to identify \n\nthe core idea, first, as it provides a foundation upon which the venture will be built.  \n\nTo  understand  this  better,  let’s  consider  the  way  many  entrepreneurs \n\ndescribe their venture by relating it to an already successful concept. For example, \n\nan  entrepreneur  may  claim  that  what  they  are  doing  is,  say,  “Uber  for  dog \n\ngrooming.” This is a useful and efficient means of communication. With those four \n\nwords, someone can readily understand that this venture is likely some form of \n\nmobile service that brings dog groomers to dog owners, on-demand. However, no \n\nmatter how useful these devices of communicating by analogy are, there is a trap \n\ninvolved in thinking this way at the outset; it does not show the many choices and \n\nentrepreneur  will  need  to  make  at  the  outset.  As  we  will  see,  below,  a  good \n\nstatement of a core idea should omit references to the venture’s initial customer \n\n(dog  owners),  technology  (mobile  applications),  organization  (network  of \n\ngroomers) and competition (traditional grooming shops). Instead, it should focus \n\nsolely on the identified opportunity. \n\n \n\x0cContinuing  on  with  our  dog  grooming  entrepreneur,  let’s  step  back  for  a \n\nmoment to try and understand what the core idea might be. At present, most dog \n\ngrooming is conducted with dog owners bringing their dogs to be groomed by a \n\nprofessional. There are some services that involve mobile dog grooming stations \n\nthat  are  booked  in  advance.  This  takes  planning.  Our  intrepid  entrepreneur, \n\nthemself a dog owner, realized that both of these current services did not serve a \n\nspecific type of problem well—what happens if a dog needs immediate grooming \n\nattention? For instance, Fido may have wallowed around in the mud and muck \n\nand is in such a state that you can’t just hose him down (especially since you have \n\nvisitors coming over soon). You don’t want to take your dog to a groomer as this \n\nwill likely spread the dirt throughout your car. You can’t wait until another slot \n\nfor a mobile dog groomer comes around. In other words, an entrepreneur might \n\ncome to realize there is some value in an on-demand solution and look for a way \n\nto solve it. \n\nNow one way you could imagine solving this problem for dog owners is to \n\nhave  dog  groomers  available  that  could  be  called  out  to  people’s  homes.  This \n\nwould involve a logistical challenge but it would be the job of the venture to solve \n\nthat.  However,  with  some more  thought, the  entrepreneur  might  come up  with \n\nother ways to solve the problem. Another way would be to transport the dirty dog \n\nto  dog  groomers  so  that  the  dog  owner  does  not  have  to  use  their  own  car.  Or \n\nperhaps the solution is to sell people some solution to allow them to transport dirty \n\ndogs in their own cars. In the end, one realizes there are numerous options and \n\neach no doubt has its own advantages and disadvantages. The point is that it is \n\nnot  necessarily  obvious  that  the  only  solution  is  something  like  Uber.  There  are \n\nother  options  and  before  embarking  on  any  one  of  them, it  is  important  that  an \n\nentrepreneur explore them.  \n\nIn this particular situation, a well-formed core idea would not be “Uber for \n\ndog groomers” but instead a venture better described as “solving the problem of \n\nhow  to  deal  with  a  dirty  animal  right  away.”  (See  BOX:  Core  ideas  for  famous \n\nstartups). The key is to state the core idea for a venture independent of key choices you will \n\nmake as you build your business idea. \n\n\x0cFor example, important choices in this venture will include: \n\n•  who the targeted set of customers are (notice that the idea stated here \n\ndoes not mention dogs but animals in general),  \n\n•  the technology that brings them there (there is no mention of an app \n\non a mobile phone),  \n\n•  who does what (there is no mention of who grooms the animal); and  \n\n•  who competitors are.  \n\nThese types of choices form the game plan of a venture and can be readily changed \n\nwhile the core idea largely stays the same. In fact, entrepreneurs face broad areas \n\nor  domains  of  choice  involving  customers,  technology,  organization,  and \n\ncompetition. In the following chapters, we will examine these further. But before \n\nwe get to that, it is important to consider why choices like these are important and \n\nthe process by which those choices can be arrived at. \n\nCore Ideas for Famous Startups \n\nA core idea of a venture is a statement of their entrepreneurial opportunity without any \nreference  to  particular  choices. Here  are some  examples  of  core  ideas  that we  have  derived for \nfamous ventures: \n\n•  Amazon: use the Internet to order and deliver goods directly to consumers \n\n•  Google: use the Internet to organize the world’s information \n\n•  Uber: use mobile technology to easily match riders with rides \n\n•  Spanx: use new materials for clothing shape and comfort \n\n•  Flickr: allow people to store and share photos over the Internet \n\n•  Slack: provide a means for members of an organization to interact with one another \n\n•  Twitter: allow sharing content quickly and easily \n\n•  Dolby:  use  advanced  sound  algorithms  to  improve  sound  recording  playback \n\nquality \n\nIn  each  case,  what  the  core  idea  describes  is  what  the  venture  is  doing  and  what  the  baseline \ntechnology is that is spurring the idea.  \n\n \n \n\x0c', 'summary_page_title': 'The Importance of Proper Benchmarks in Mutual Fund Performance Evaluation', '_user_id': 'user1', '_id': '8131177fae8dc79837bd385ed6689577accd79028899d07c972d8e0e13822b2d2fa03af6ca5654532ebad02e50404c2f874abfb88160cd7912137d9b83b2f6d7', 'content_display_URL': True, 'content_written': False}>
